{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c48edfb-6bcd-4a3d-97a8-e30da81621de","content":"Here's the migration path:\n\n### 1. Add/update `Directory.Build.props` at the solution root\n\nThis sets properties consistently across all three projects:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** — switches MSTest 3.8.0 from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n- **`OutputType Exe`** — required because each test project now runs as its own executable.\n- **`TrxReport` package** — replaces the VSTest TRX logger; without it, `--report-trx` won't be recognized.\n\n### 2. Clean up each `.csproj`\n\nRemove any per-project `<OutputType>` or `<EnableMSTestRunner>` if they already exist (they're now in `Directory.Build.props`). No other `.csproj` changes are needed — your existing `Microsoft.Testing.Platform`-compatible MSTest 3.8.0 package references stay as-is.\n\n### 3. Update the CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\n`--logger trx` is a VSTest concept. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, arguments after `--` are passed directly to the test runner. `--report-trx` is provided by the `TrxReport` extension and writes `.trx` files to the `TestResults/` folder, same as before.\n\n### Summary of what changed and why\n\n| Area | Before (VSTest) | After (Testing.Platform) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Runner | VSTest host process | Each test project is its own `Exe` |\n| Runner opt-in | *(none)* | `EnableMSTestRunner=true` |\n| TRX reports | Built-in `--logger trx` | NuGet package + `-- --report-trx` |\n| `dotnet test` | Works directly | Still works (bridge/compat layer in SDK) |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"32e38677-825c-4806-b6ba-4441f4a5a950","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Enable Microsoft.Testing.Platform in each project (or centrally via Directory.Build.props)\n2. **CI command**: Update the `dotnet test` command\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0, the migration involves:\n- Adding `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each test project, OR using `<UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>` in Directory.Build.props\n\n\n- For TRX report generation, you'll need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package to enable the TRX logger with the new platform\n- In CI environments, `dotnet test` still works, but with Microsoft.Testing.Platform you use `--report-trx` instead of the traditional `--logger trx` flag\n- The cleanest approach is to set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in a `Directory.Build.props` file for consistency across all test projects rather than configuring each one individually Configuring the Directory.Build.props file... For .NET 8 SDK, `dotnet test` should still work with Microsoft.Testing.Platform projects through a compatibility layer, even though the SDK defaults to VSTest for traditional test frameworks.\n\nI'm setting up the configuration with `EnableMSTestRunner` and `OutputType` as Exe in a shared build props file, then adding the TRX reporting package to capture test results. The CI command would use `dotnet test -- --report-trx` to generate the report, though I should verify whether the older `--logger trx` syntax still works with the new platform or if it requires the different argument format.","outputTokens":2157,"requestId":"67E8:141F12:295CB56:2DA3952:69FD33F0"},"id":"00efe89c-0687-4176-a490-4803f1fb14e4","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:53:45.573Z","parentId":"86e4ea01-74fc-4f15-975d-ccadbfb4c45a"}
